name: PluralKit Example System
description:
This is an example of what a PluralKit system card looks like. This description can be up to 1000 characters long, and can contain **formatting** and ðŸ’Ž emojis âœ¨. What you see above, "PluralKit Example System", is the system's name. 
 
The system's *tag*, displayed above, is added to the end of the member name when proxying. This helps identify systems cohesively. 
 
For a list of commands change that change system cards like these, type `pk;commands system`. 
  
This system has a secret private member with the ID `cmpuv`. They won't show up in the member list, but you can look them up to by ID see what information is visible.
